<title>RUSSIA: AGROKHLEB-Ukraine livestock sector shrinks.</title>
<headline>AGROKHLEB-Ukraine livestock sector shrinks.</headline>
<text>
<p>The following is a direct contribution from SovEcon Ltd, an independent research organisation specialising in agricultural production and trade in the former Soviet Union, in association with Ukragroconsult, a private Ukrainian agricultural consultancy based in Kiev.</p>
<p>PRIVATE FARMS OUTDO PUBLIC IN UKRAINIAN LIVESTOCK SECTOR</p>
<p>KIEV, July 18 - Over January-June 1997, Ukraine's total meat and milk production fell six percent and 18 percent, respectively (Table 1). The decrease comes from a deep recession in the public farm sector.</p>
<p>Cattle, cow and pig numbers in the public sector dropped 20, 15 and 13 percent, respectively, leading to output drops of 16 percent for meat and 35 percent for milk.</p>
<p>In contrast, output by the private farm sector is rather stable.</p>
<p>Over January-June, meat and milk production and cattle numbers on private farms remained nearly at last year's levels, while pig numbers increased 24 percent.</p>
<p>Over that time period, the private sector accounted for 61 percent of national meat output and 59 percent of milk production; the numbers for that period in 1996 were 56 and 58 percent.</p>
<p>Cattle numbers on private farms had grown to 28 percent as of July 1997 from 24 percent in July 1996. Cows had grown to 46 from 40 percent, and pigs to 48 from 40 percent.</p>
